---

# Skill: legate.dispatch (new-work mechanics)

This skill picks ready Smithy work items, syncs the default branch, and launches new workers. Load it **last** on every heartbeat (after resume → babysit → merge → cleanup). Run it **regardless of what babysit found** — new dispatches create new workers on new branches in new worktrees and don't interfere with in-flight PRs that babysit is shepherding. Iterate over every ready item and launch one worker per item that doesn't already have one.

Load via `Skill(skill="legate.dispatch")`. The classifier registers the allowed-tools for the rest of the session.

---

## When to dispatch

Run this protocol on **every** heartbeat — there is no babysit-clean gate. A PR sitting in `pr-in-fix`, `pr-rebasing`, `pr-in-rerun`, or `pr-resolving-conflicts` does not block new dispatch: each new worker lives in its own worktree on its own branch, so a stuck implementation slice has no contention with a fresh `smithy.cut`/`smithy.forge`/`smithy.mark`/`smithy.render` on a different artifact. The previous "babysit must be clean" gate stranded conductors for hours when one PR was cycling fix-comments; that gate is removed.

For each ready item from `smithy status`, dispatch when all of the following hold:

1. **`smithy status` reports it as ready** with a non-null `next_action`. Use the wrapper script (below) — never compose `smithy` commands directly.
2. **All dependencies have merged PRs.** Check `state.json.archived_slices.<id>` first, but count it only when `terminal_state == "MERGED"` or `merged_at` is present; a `terminal_state == "CLOSED"` archive only means the worker was cleaned up. Then fall back to `state.json.slices.<id>` with `pr.state == "MERGED"` if cleanup hasn't archived yet (look for `last_action_note: "cleanup failed: ..."` to know that's why). Do not preempt the merge gate — an unmerged forge predecessor blocks the dependent forge regardless of how many heartbeats have elapsed.
3. **No worker is already in flight for this artifact.** Look for an existing `state.json.slices.<id>` whose `command` + `arguments` (or `branch`) match this ready item. If one exists in any non-terminal stage, skip this item — the existing worker owns it. Do not stack a second worker on the same slice.

Items that pass all three are dispatched. The order matters when multiple items are ready: see *Prioritization* below.

There is **no hard cap on dispatches per heartbeat**. Launch one worker per ready, undispatched, dep-merged item in this heartbeat. The natural rate limit is "items that pass the three gates above", and `launch-worker.sh` is the only path that creates sessions — so the dispatch count is bounded by the size of the ready set, not by an arbitrary tick budget.

---

## The protocol

### 1. Refresh smithy status

```
.claude/skills/legate.dispatch/scripts/smithy-status.sh {{REPO_PATH}}
```

Returns Smithy's view of what's ready (full report — every record, including done and virtual ones). The conductor's `state.json` is the source of truth for *what's already dispatched*; cross-reference to find work items that exist in `smithy status` but not in `state.json.slices`.

To filter that report down to dispatchable items, **always use the wrapper script** — never inline `python3 -c`, `jq`, `bash -c`, or `node -e` against the JSON. Inline interpreters are explicitly NEED-escalations under the legate's auto-mode rules and will pause the loop on every heartbeat:

```
.claude/skills/legate.dispatch/scripts/find-ready-slices.sh {{REPO_PATH}}
```

Returns a JSON array of `{type, path, title, status, next_action}` for every record where `next_action != null` and `virtual` is false (i.e. ready, dispatchable items). Empty array `[]` is the legitimate quiescent state — nothing to launch this heartbeat.

Prioritization, in order. Each ready item from `smithy status` carries a `next_action.command` drawn from the closed set {`smithy.render`, `smithy.mark`, `smithy.cut`, `smithy.forge`} — those are the only four verbs the status emitter ever produces. Dispatch off that field rather than guessing the verb from the artifact type.

1. **Cuts for any user story that is ready** (`next_action.command == "smithy.cut"`). Cuts on different specs, or on different user-stories within the same spec, are independent and run in parallel as separate workers — they touch separate tasks files.
2. **Forges for any slice whose dependencies are merged** (`next_action.command == "smithy.forge"`). Forges on independent slices run in parallel; forges on dependent slices wait for the predecessor's PR to merge (visible in either `slices.<dep-id>` with `pr.state == "MERGED"` or `archived_slices.<dep-id>` with `terminal_state == "MERGED"` / `merged_at`) before being dispatched.
3. **Planning-chain steps for upstream artifacts** (`next_action.command` ∈ {`smithy.render`, `smithy.mark`}), in the order `smithy status` recommends. These are the verbs that produce the artifacts cut/forge then consume:
   - `smithy.render` — produces a feature map (`.features.md`) from an RFC milestone.
   - `smithy.mark` — produces a spec folder (`.spec.md`/`.data-model.md`/`.contracts.md`) from a feature in a feature map.

   Do **not** silently skip a `smithy.mark` or `smithy.render` next_action just because no cut/forge is queued — they are the upstream of the same chain and must be dispatched the same way. The verb-cmd is `/<command> <arguments joined by spaces>` straight from `next_action`.

`smithy.audit` is intentionally **not** in the dispatch surface: `smithy status` never recommends it (audit is a read-only review against a specific artifact, not a forward-chain step). Operators invoke it manually when they want a second pass. Leave it for them.

### 2. Sync the default branch

**Required before every new-work dispatch.** New worker sessions branch off whatever HEAD `{{REPO_PATH}}` points at. If you skip this step and a previous PR merged since you last fetched, the new worker silently builds on stale code and produces a PR that's already behind.

```
.claude/skills/legate.dispatch/scripts/sync-default-branch.sh {{REPO_PATH}}
```

Returns JSON `{"default_branch": "...", "synced": true, "head": "<sha>"}`. Cache `default_branch` into `state.json.repo.default_branch` on first detection — it does not change for the life of a conductor.

The script uses `git pull --ff-only` and exits non-zero on divergence rather than forcing. If it fails, **escalate** — do not `git reset --hard` or force-update. The worker should not launch until the operator resolves the divergence.

### 3. Launch the worker

```
.claude/skills/legate.dispatch/scripts/launch-worker.sh \
  {{PROFILE}} {{REPO_PATH}} "<slice-title>" {{WORKER_GROUP}} <branch> <verb-cmd> <slice-id>
```

- `slice-title`: name the title `<verb>: <artifact-id>`, e.g. `cut: spawn-dispatch US5`, `forge: spawn-dispatch S3`, `mark: 01-spawn F3`, `render: march-orchestration-platform M2`.
- `branch`: the worktree branch name; you choose (e.g. `smithy/cut/spawn-dispatch-us5`, `smithy/mark/01-spawn-f3`). Note: `/smithy.*` slash-commands may rename this when they push (see SmithyCLI#297) — the babysit skill's `discover-pr.sh` handles that case.
- `verb-cmd`: the initial message to send — formed by joining `next_action.command` and `next_action.arguments`. Examples:
  - cut: `/smithy.cut specs/2026-04-11-002-spawn-dispatch 5`
  - forge: `/smithy.forge specs/2026-04-11-002-spawn-dispatch/05-launch-container-with-security-config.tasks.md 1`
  - mark: `/smithy.mark docs/rfcs/2026-001-march-orchestration-platform/01-spawn.features.md 3`
  - render: `/smithy.render docs/rfcs/2026-001-march-orchestration-platform/march-orchestration-platform.rfc.md 2`
- `slice-id`: the same id you'll record under `state.json.slices.<slice-id>`. Must match `^[a-zA-Z0-9][a-zA-Z0-9._-]*$` (it goes into a filename). Pick a short stable derivation of the artifact (e.g. `spawn-dispatch-us5-cut`, `cli-foundation-us2-s1`).

Returns JSON `{"session_id": "...", "branch": "...", "worktree_path": "..."}`. The script atomically creates the worktree, launches the Claude session under your worker group, locks the title (#agent-deck-697), pins auto-mode permission via `--permission-mode auto`, and sends the initial slash command.

**Recovery stage:** before launching, the script writes the `verb-cmd` to `./dispatch-msg-<slice-id>.md` in your cwd (the conductor dir). If agent-deck later revives the worker after a host restart, the revived Claude Code process comes back fresh and does NOT replay the original `-m` argument — the slice ends up recorded as `implementing` but the worker pane is an empty splash. `legate.babysit` reads this file when it detects the revival signature (`stage=implementing`, status idle/waiting, no PR, no recent worker output) and re-sends the contents via `send-to-worker.sh`. Do not delete `dispatch-msg-*.md` files by hand; `legate.cleanup` removes them when the slice merges.

Three launch flags are non-negotiable for workers — the script wires them all:

- `--worktree "<slice-branch>" -b` — each worker gets its own git worktree on a new branch. Without this, concurrent workers fight over `{{REPO_PATH}}`'s working tree and step on each other's commits.
- `--title-lock` — Claude Code's session auto-rename will otherwise overwrite the title you set, breaking title-based session resolution.
- `-c claude` — agent runtime. Codex workers are not supported by this prompt.

Worker sessions and their worktrees are auto-cleaned by `legate.cleanup` after a slice merges. At dispatch time you do not need to think about teardown — when babysit transitions a slice to `merged`, cleanup (which runs after babysit and before dispatch on the same heartbeat) removes the session via `agent-deck session remove --prune-worktree --force` and moves the slice's record into `archived_slices`. Capture `worktree_path` into `state.json` here for cleanup's bookkeeping; the entry will be moved out of `slices` after the merge. Brood (Milestone 3) will own broader lifecycle cleanup.

### 4. Capture session details

The launch script returns the new session ID and worktree path in its JSON output. To re-confirm or fetch additional fields (e.g. `claude_session_id`, `parent_session_id`, current `status`), use:

```
.claude/skills/legate.dispatch/scripts/inspect-worker.sh {{PROFILE}} <session-id-or-title>
```

This wraps `agent-deck session show --json`. **Always go through this script** — calling `agent-deck session show` directly is what historically stalled the heartbeat loop, because it sits outside both skills' `allowed-tools` and trips the auto-mode classifier on a permission prompt.

### 5. Record into `state.json`

Add a new entry under `slices.<slice-id>` per the schema in `CLAUDE.md`:

```json
{
  "worker_session_id": "<from launch-worker JSON>",
  "worker_title": "<slice-title>",
  "branch": "<launch branch>",
  "actual_branch": null,
  "worktree_path": "<from launch-worker JSON>",
  "stage": "implementing",
  "pr": null,
  "last_action": "<ISO-8601 now>",
  "last_action_note": "Launched <slice-title> via /smithy.<verb>"
}
```

`actual_branch` and `pr.number` are filled in by `legate.babysit` on the next heartbeat where `discover-pr.sh` finds the URL the worker printed when it ran `gh pr create` — typically the worker's `running → waiting` transition, but babysit also runs discovery when an `implementing`-stage worker has passed straight through to `idle`.

### 6. Loop or stop

You launched one worker. If more items in the ready set pass the three gates (ready, deps merged, no in-flight worker on the same artifact), repeat steps 3–5 for each — there is no per-heartbeat dispatch cap. When the ready set is exhausted (or every remaining item is blocked by a still-in-flight worker on the same artifact), yield back to the conductor for its `[STATUS]` reply.

Each launch is serialized: complete the worker creation + `state.json` write for slice N before starting slice N+1, so a failure on N+1 doesn't leave N half-recorded. Re-call `find-ready-slices.sh` between launches if a long-running launch could have changed the ready set (unusual, but harmless to re-check).

---

## Worker session configuration

Workers run in **auto mode** (`--permission-mode auto`) — Claude Code's classifier auto-approves routine edits/commits/tests and surfaces genuinely risky actions for review. agent-deck's group/conductor TOML blocks only support `config_dir` and `env_file`, **not** `auto_mode` (that key only lives on the global `[claude]` block, which would affect every Claude session on the host). To scope auto mode to legate's workers, the launch script passes `--permission-mode auto` per-launch via agent-deck's `--extra-arg`.

`--dangerously-skip-permissions` (the yolo flag, mapped from agent-deck's `dangerous_mode`) is the *escape valve* for a specific slice that keeps stalling on auto mode's classifier. Don't default to it; escalate first and let the operator opt into dangerous mode for one slice via `agent-deck session set <worker> extra-args -- --dangerously-skip-permissions` rather than flipping the safer default off for everyone.

---

## Operation reference

| Operation | Script | Returns |
|---|---|---|
| Refresh smithy status | `smithy-status.sh <repo-path>` | smithy's status output (JSON) |
| Sync default branch | `sync-default-branch.sh <repo-path>` | JSON `{default_branch, synced, head}` |
| Launch worker for slice | `launch-worker.sh <profile> <repo> <title> <group> <branch> <verb-cmd>` | JSON `{session_id, branch, worktree_path}` |
| Inspect worker | `inspect-worker.sh <profile> <session-id-or-title>` | JSON from `agent-deck session show` |

All scripts emit JSON to stdout, progress to stderr, and exit 0/1/2 for success/op-failure/invalid-input.

## Standing rules

- **No per-heartbeat cap on dispatch count.** Launch one worker per item in the ready set that passes the three gates (ready, deps merged, no in-flight worker on the same artifact). The natural rate limit is the size of the ready set.
- **No babysit-clean gate.** Dispatch runs every heartbeat regardless of what babysit found. A PR in `pr-in-fix`/`pr-rebasing`/`pr-in-rerun`/`pr-resolving-conflicts` is babysit's problem to shepherd; dispatching new work on a different artifact does not interfere with it.
- **Sync default before launching.** Always. Skipping this is how stale-base PRs slip out. Sync once per heartbeat before the first launch, not per-launch.
- **Never bypass the merge gate.** Forges wait for their dependency PRs to merge. Cuts on parallel user stories are fine; cuts that depend on each other are not.
- **One worker per artifact.** If `state.json.slices.<id>` already exists for an artifact in a non-terminal stage, do not stack a second worker on it. The in-flight worker owns the work.
- **`launch-worker.sh` is the only path that creates new sessions.** Don't compose `agent-deck launch` directly — the script wires the non-negotiable flags (`--worktree -b --title-lock --extra-arg ...`).
